  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3672745967" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3672745967" />
    <a title="Susan in NC" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/883451-susan-in-nc"><img alt="Susan in NC" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1625869869p2/883451.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3672745967?book_show_action=true">Dec 03, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Susan in NC" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Susan in NC" href="/user/show/883451-susan-in-nc">Susan in NC</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/6473211-the-adventure-of-the-christmas-pudding">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3672745967" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4009529889587198122">As with all short story collections, some are weaker than others, but overall a fun collection- seemed odd to have the Miss Marple story here, it’s not Christmas themed or otherwise related.<br/><br/>I read and reviewed “The Adventure of the Christmas pudding” as a short story, didn’t realize it was a collection. Here is my review of that story- <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/56055645-the-adventure-of-the-christmas-pudding-a-hercule-poirot-mystery?from_search=true&amp;from_srp=true&amp;qid=Oc7s9fI5uQ&amp;rank=10'>https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5...</a>.<br/><br/>I’ll read the rest of the collection and review each story.<br/><br/>Mystery of the Spanish Chest - 3.5 stars - interesting, I’ve s</span>
  <span id="freeText4009529889587198122" style="display:none">As with all short story collections, some are weaker than others, but overall a fun collection- seemed odd to have the Miss Marple story here, it’s not Christmas themed or otherwise related.<br /><br />I read and reviewed “The Adventure of the Christmas pudding” as a short story, didn’t realize it was a collection. Here is my review of that story- <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/56055645-the-adventure-of-the-christmas-pudding-a-hercule-poirot-mystery?from_search=true&amp;from_srp=true&amp;qid=Oc7s9fI5uQ&amp;rank=10">https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5...</a>.<br /><br />I’ll read the rest of the collection and review each story.<br /><br />Mystery of the Spanish Chest - 3.5 stars - interesting, I’ve seen the David Suchet version on tv, but couldn’t remember whodunnit. Seemed like a sure thing that the arrested man killed the husband of the femme fatale because he wanted her for himself. Poirot is captivated by the drama of the news stories, but then the widow asks him to investigate. Poirot meets all the characters involved, and of course there is a twist only he can see!<br /><br />The Underdog - 3.5 stars - never read or seen this one, to my knowledge- interesting to see Poirot using his manservant George as an assistant on a case. Lady Astwell has called him in to investigate her husband’s murder; she’s convinced the police have arrested the wrong man. As usual, Poirot questions through conversation, forms his own theories, and catches the killer - unmasking the true motives and alliances hiding amongst the household! Entertaining story.<br /><br />Four and Twenty Blackbirds - 4 stars - this really appealed to me, as a good example of tight plotting, without any padding, young lovers, etc. Poirot is dining with a friend as the story opens; the friend tells of a regular customer who only ever ate there Tuesdays and Thursdays, like clockwork, but suddenly came in on a Monday. Then wasn’t seen for awhile, then is found dead. Poirot gets suspicious of this odd behavior and starts digging, finds the clues to change an accidental death to murder, and get the killer. Satisfying, solid, spare plot.<br /><br />The Dream -3 stars - had seen this on tv with Suchet, which was fun and more fleshed out as I recall, more padding with the usual “young lovers” subplot. The original story is much more streamlined, with an interesting premise of a very rich man having a recurring dream foretelling his death by suicide, but of course Poirot suspects and proves murder when the man is eventually found dead. Seemed very intricate and rife with possibilities for failure of the murder plot.<br /><br />Greenshaw’s Folly - 3 stars - the only Miss Marple story, this was not a favorite, but I remember seeing it on TV at some point. Like The Dream, seemed rather over-elaborate and convoluted for a short story - as always, Miss Marple sees through the fog and has all the answers, but it seemed a bit too far-fetched and coincidental.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4009529889587198122" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


